(- Falcon-512 for signatures.) Tj
T*
(- SHA3-384-derived key and transaction hashing.) Tj
T*
(- Base56 address format for user-facing workflows.) Tj
T*
(- Internal normalized HPK representation for deterministic processing.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(5.2 Ledger and Validation) Tj
T*
(Atho uses a UTXO ledger with explicit spent/locked semantics, canonical transaction hashing, fee) Tj
T*
(and dust policy enforcement, and coinbase limits tied to reward schedule plus fees.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(5.3 Consensus and Chain Integrity) Tj
T*
(Block acceptance verifies linkage, structure, signatures, target bounds, and payout correctness.) Tj
T*
(Reorg/orphan handling is treated as a normal consensus path.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Current PoW retargeting uses a deterministic interval-based weighted-median window on production) Tj
T*
(networks: target block time is 120 seconds, retarget every 360 blocks, clamp per-epoch) Tj
T*
(adjustment ratio to 0.60..1.85, clamp interval outliers, and weight recent intervals more) Tj
T*
(heavily for responsiveness without excessive volatility. Timestamp safety uses median-time-past) Tj
T*
(\(MTP_WINDOW=13\) plus bounded future drift \(MAX_TIME_DRIFT=120 seconds\) across verifier and) Tj
T*
(direct chain-accept paths to reduce timestamp-manipulation attack surface. User-facing) Tj
T*
(confirmation policy is 10 confirmations for regular transactions and 400 confirmations for) Tj
T*
(coinbase maturity.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(5.4 Storage and APIs) Tj
T*
(LMDB-backed stores track blocks, UTXOs, mempool data, and state metadata. The API surface is) Tj
T*
(role-aware:) Tj
T*
(- full node for canonical chain state,) Tj
T*
(- miner for PoW and candidate flow,) Tj
T*
(- wallet/API for address and transaction operations.) Tj
T*
(- PQC Full-Stack Key Protection at Rest) Tj
T*
(Atho?s key-at-rest model is hybrid by design: it combines post-quantum key encapsulation with) Tj
T*
(high-assurance symmetric encryption.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(6.1 What is encrypted) Tj
T*
(- Wallet secret payload: Falcon private key parts and mnemonic recovery material.) Tj
T*
(- Payload is encrypted with **AES-256-GCM** using a random DEK \(data-encryption key\).) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(6.2 How unlock works \(two control planes\)) Tj
T*
(- Password plane:) Tj
T*
(- User password -> Argon2id -> KEK.) Tj
T*
(- KEK unwraps DEK \(AES-256-GCM wrap record\).) Tj
T*
(- DEK decrypts payload.) Tj
T*
(- PQ plane:) Tj
T*
(- Kyber KEM record \(ciphertext + metadata\) also wraps the same DEK.) Tj
T*
(- Advanced unlock/recovery mode can restore DEK through Kyber material.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(6.3 Why Kyber + AES together) Tj
T*
(- AES-256-GCM is efficient and authenticated for bulk payload encryption.) Tj
T*
(- Kyber is used for KEM/wrap semantics, not bulk data encryption.) Tj
T*
(- Using both gives practical performance now and a post-quantum recovery path.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(6.4 Security interpretation) Tj
T*
(- If password handling is weak, Kyber path still gives a separate cryptographic control plane) Tj
T*
ET
endstream
